05901nam a22010095i 9783110473674DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20162016gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)956320688  a97831104736747 a10.1515/97831104736742doi  a(DE-B1597)463702  a(OCoLC)946712283  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a401.900aAction, Decision-Making and Forms of Life /ced. by Jesús Padilla Gálvez. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (V, 173 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAporia ,x2197-862X ;v900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAction, Decision-Making and Forms of Life -- tThe Quest for Knowledge as a Form of Life: Collective Thought and Decision in Science -- tIntuition, Decision, Compulsion -- tActions Embedded in Forms of Life -- tAction and Decision-Making -- tWittgenstein on the Will and Voluntary Action -- tMoral Epistemology, Interpersonal Indeterminacy and Enactivism -- tStructures, Dynamisms and Contents of Our Belief System: Husserl and Wittgenstein -- t‘Hinges’ and the Boundaries of Epistemic Agency -- tDecisions, Actions, and Forms of Personal Life -- tAbbreviations of Wittgenstein’s Works -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book is exceptional because it applies the notion of foms of life to the context of human action. It provides answers to the following questions: Why do we act in a specific way? Why do we make particular decisions? Does one's form of life and language games determine our actions and decisions? Wittgenstein proposes a holistic method which enables us to give coherent answers to these questions. To answer the question of the contents of actions and decisions we have to explain how we have institutionalized these actions or decisions. To this aim we shall reveal the frame within which language games are introduced and have come to function as practice and custom. The scheme of order underlying the language games is illustrated. Human actions and decisions follow particular rules. By highlighting the underlying scheme of order we may gain a perspicuous view of these rules. The aim of this book is to show that actions and decisions generate rational choice. This choice is explained by demonstrating the particular functions of the language games involved.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAct (Philosophy). 0aDecision making. 0aLanguage and languagesxPhilosophy. 0aLife. 4aEntscheidung. 4aHandlungstheorie. 4aSprachspiel. 4aWittgenstein, Ludwig. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aTheory of action.  aWittgenstein, Ludwig.  adecision.  alanguage games.1 aGaffal, Margit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález-Castán, Óscar L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGómez-Alonso, Modesto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe Du, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aObsieger, Bernhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPadilla Gálvez, Jesús, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPadilla Gálvez, Jesús, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSalvatore, Nicola Claudio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchroeder, Severin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVenturinha, Nuno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2016 Part 1z978311076250108iTitle is p